 MBOMBELA – A five-cent increase in the fuel price means that Lowvelders will now be paying R16,32 for a litre of petrol. Lowvelder previously found that Lowvelders pay more for fuel due to transport costs. Kuzi Maya, from Puma, explained that the closer you live to the coast, the cheaper the fuel is because there are fewer transport costs involved. READ ALSO: Fuel increase: Why Lowvelders pay more than the rest of SA With the increase at midnight, this means that Lowvelders will be paying 83 cents more for a litre of 95 petrol than coastal dwellers and 24 cents more than the inland price. Minister of Energy Jeff Radebe has confirmed that his department is stepping in to ease the hikes in petrol prices. READ ALSO: The real price of fuel in South Africa